// Below concept is only applicable for class objects where class might has pointer members (Not for pointers objects)

🔹 Shallow Copy

    Copies all member variables of an object bit by bit.
    If the class contains pointers, the copied object’s pointer points to the same memory as the original.
    Both objects share the same data → changing one affects the other.
    Can cause double deletion if both try to free the same memory.

🔹 Deep Copy

    Copies all data including dynamically allocated memory.
    Each object gets its own separate copy of the data.
    Safe and independent — no shared memory.


| Feature                  | **Shallow Copy**             | **Deep Copy**     |
| ------------------------ | ---------------------------- | ----------------- |
| Memory Allocation        | Shared                       | Separate          |
| Pointer Members          | Point to same memory         | Copy new memory   |
| Default Copy Constructor | Yes                          | No (user-defined) |
| Independence             | No                           | Yes               |
| Risk                     | Double free, data corruption | None              |


Note: In C++, if your class contains pointers (or any dynamically allocated resources), and you want a deep copy, then you must define your own copy constructor (and often assignment operator) to implement that behavior yourself.

Note:  For shallow copy, explicit copy constructor is not required
Ex: for Deep copy,

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class A {
    int* data;
public:
    // Normal constructor
    A(int val) {
        data = new int(val);
    }

    // Deep copy constructor
    A(const A& obj) {
        data = new int(*obj.data);   // allocate new memory and copy value
    }

    // Show method
    void show() { cout << *data << endl; }

    ~A() {
        delete data;
        cout << "Destructor called\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    A a1(10);
    A a2 = a1;    // calls deep copy constructor
    a2.show();
}
